WEBVTT

00:21.666 --> 00:22.427
What are you doing?

00:23.829 --> 00:24.510
Planting this tree.

00:25.892 --> 00:27.114
Right, that's a small tree.

00:27.614 --> 00:28.375
Yeah, it'll get bigger.

00:29.417 --> 00:30.018
Tomorrow?

00:31.820 --> 00:32.561
No, not tomorrow.

00:33.783 --> 00:34.324
Wind then.

00:36.006 --> 00:37.388
Long after I'm gone.

00:37.428 --> 00:39.631
Many years.

00:40.753 --> 00:45.239
Maybe by the time you get to be my age, it'll be big enough to provide shade.

00:46.420 --> 00:47.602
Well, that's not fair.

00:49.538 --> 00:51.820
Do you enjoy swinging on the rope in your yard?

00:52.961 --> 00:53.742
Yeah.

00:53.762 --> 00:54.583
Who planted that tree?

00:56.485 --> 00:58.307
Uh...

00:58.327 --> 01:00.309
It's always been there.

01:00.329 --> 01:00.529
No.

01:01.510 --> 01:08.457
That tree was planted by someone generations ago so that you could play in its shade.

01:10.819 --> 01:11.580
I'm just doing the same.

01:12.101 --> 01:13.782
Oh, bugs lifting it, squirrels?

01:14.543 --> 01:17.586
Yes, yeah, but when it's big and it'll be a home,

01:18.402 --> 01:19.724
for all the wildlife.

01:21.526 --> 01:22.747
Who will water that tree?

01:23.068 --> 01:23.388
I will.

01:25.791 --> 01:26.391
Do you want to help?

01:27.333 --> 01:27.853
Yeah.

01:30.676 --> 01:35.162
All right, here you go.

01:36.804 --> 01:38.426
All right, let's go over here.

01:40.028 --> 01:41.129
Got water all the way around.

01:43.612 --> 01:45.554
That's good.

02:46.562 --> 02:47.943
Welcome to the Well Community Church.

02:47.984 --> 02:49.605
So glad you're hanging out with us here today.

02:49.645 --> 02:50.807
Happy New Year to everyone.

02:50.847 --> 02:52.348
If we have not met yet, my name's Brad.

02:52.368 --> 02:57.574
I get the privilege of handling God's word here together and launching a little bit of a series for us.

02:57.594 --> 03:06.463
This is going to be a four-week journey as we sort of lay out some of the back story behind what the Lord is doing here and some of the why behind next steps that we are looking to take.

03:06.524 --> 03:11.269
And so I want to say welcome, of course, to those here at our Clovis campus, to those over in our family venue.

03:11.289 --> 03:16.274
So grateful for you are hanging out over there and then those joining us online or over at our fig garden.

03:16.386 --> 03:16.847
campus.

03:16.867 --> 03:18.690
We've got a lot going on here at the well.

03:18.710 --> 03:21.895
It's just so grateful to be a part of what God is doing here in our city.

03:22.556 --> 03:26.322
I want to begin our journey together by kind of rewinding the tapes a little bit.

03:26.402 --> 03:29.707
I want to take you back all the way back to 1862.

03:30.188 --> 03:38.321
After our country had fought the bloodiest war we have ever fought in the history of these young United States of America, we fought the Civil War.

03:38.561 --> 03:41.746
As the Civil War came to an end, there was

03:41.890 --> 03:44.693
a focus renewed on conquering the West.

03:44.793 --> 03:47.336
What does Western expansion look like?

03:47.376 --> 03:52.982
And in fact, in 1862, Abraham Lincoln signed what was called the Homestead Act.

03:53.502 --> 04:08.178
And the Homestead Act incentivized settlers who had the courage and the persistence and the tenacity to head west to the unsettled land, follow the path of Lewis and Clark that they had laid before them and head

04:08.290 --> 04:11.135
to the West to establish themselves out here.

04:11.335 --> 04:27.401
And in that, anyone was eligible who was a U.S. citizen or intended to be a U.S. citizen or even an immigrant that had come to this country, even those who were freed slaves, all had the opportunity to come and to establish themselves in the West.

04:27.501 --> 04:31.447
They would receive in this agreement 160 acres.

04:32.248 --> 04:35.794
The requirement was they had to cultivate the land.

04:36.098 --> 04:37.500
You had to build a home on it.

04:37.620 --> 04:39.943
There's no rentals in this agreement.

04:40.403 --> 04:46.271
You had to build a home on it, and you had to cultivate either the land or livestock or both.

04:46.911 --> 04:50.916
And in so doing, you would pay $1.25 per acre.

04:51.497 --> 04:58.005
So for $200, you can have yourselves 160 acres out in the Western US.

04:58.065 --> 04:59.267
Now, it would not be easy.

04:59.307 --> 05:05.234
Of course, it came with tremendous risk, tremendous courage, tremendous personal investment, but of course, the West

05:05.474 --> 05:06.495
was finally settled.

05:07.056 --> 05:10.419
I want you to take the same concept, but let's go back in time a little bit farther.

05:10.439 --> 05:13.362
Let's go all the way back to 2000 BC.

05:13.502 --> 05:23.092
And let's ask and answer the question, how did someone like Abraham in Genesis chapter 12, how did he establish himself in the land?

05:23.112 --> 05:26.615
If you have your Bible, go ahead and turn to Genesis chapter 12.

05:27.796 --> 05:30.859
There was no Western expansion in the time of Abraham.

05:30.899 --> 05:33.522
There was no Homestead Act.

05:33.634 --> 05:36.858
In fact, no real borders whatsoever.

05:37.118 --> 05:40.522
There were no countries, not like we know them today.

05:40.582 --> 05:47.089
There were ancient civilizations, but they weren't necessarily as established as we're used to in our day.

05:47.510 --> 05:57.221
And in fact, there were really just kind of scattered civilizations throughout the ancient world, most of them very small, most of them regional, most of them just sort of city-states.

05:57.501 --> 06:02.066
And that's sort of the backdrop now of Genesis chapter 12, and technically,

06:02.146 --> 06:04.048
the final verse of chapter 11.

06:04.249 --> 06:13.020
In fact, in chapter 11 verse 31 of Genesis, we're introduced to the biblical character Abram, whose name means exalted father, his name is gonna be changed to Abraham.

06:13.521 --> 06:16.805
Ruach is added to his name, it means exalted father of the multitudes.

06:16.865 --> 06:29.842
And so Abram or Abraham now is with his father in verse 31 of chapter 11, and they are called by God to leave their homeland, which is Ur of the Chaldeans, and to go then to the land of Canaan.

06:30.370 --> 06:35.455
And so he goes from the land of Ur of the Chaldines to Haran and he settles there.

06:35.475 --> 06:36.917
Now, where is Ur of the Chaldines?

06:37.277 --> 06:39.379
We would know it as modern-day Iraq.

06:39.399 --> 06:45.325
It was known as ancient Mesopotamia, but specifically the civilization known as the Sumerians.

06:45.345 --> 06:47.968
Not to be confused with the New Testament Samaritans.

06:48.008 --> 06:49.730
Those are different civilizations.

06:49.810 --> 06:53.314
The Sumerians were a brilliant ancient civilization.

06:53.794 --> 06:57.458
We tend to function on what some have called chronological arrogance.

06:57.666 --> 07:03.033
And it's the assumption that the older we get, like the more modern the civilization, the more brilliant.

07:03.093 --> 07:05.537
But that's not necessarily the case.

07:06.077 --> 07:11.345
The Sumerians invented or at least perfected the wheel, soon-aformed script.

07:12.626 --> 07:17.533
They were masters in botany, masters in horticulture, masters in hydrology.

07:17.573 --> 07:19.336
They invented irrigation.

07:19.456 --> 07:21.699
They knew how to flourish in the desert.

07:21.719 --> 07:25.324
And so that's now the backdrop of chapter 12, verses one through four.

07:25.344 --> 07:27.026
It says, the Lord now says to Abram,

07:27.234 --> 07:32.840
go forth from your country, from your relatives, and from your father's house, to the land that I will show you.

07:33.560 --> 07:40.127
I will make you a great nation, I will bless you, and I will make your name great, and so you shall be a blessing.

07:40.688 --> 07:44.692
And I will bless those who bless you, and the one who curses you, I will curse.

07:46.213 --> 07:54.962
And in you, all the families of the earth will be blessed, and so verse four, Abram went forth as the Lord had spoken to him, and the Lord went with him,

07:55.138 --> 07:59.207
And Abram was 75 years old when he departed from Haran.

07:59.427 --> 08:03.676
And so you've got in verses one through four what's commonly called the Abrahamic Covenant.

08:03.696 --> 08:08.847
It's one of the most significant Old Testament covenants in your Bible because it's an unconditional covenant.

08:09.328 --> 08:11.393
God will swear literally by himself.

08:11.613 --> 08:12.996
He makes an oath by himself.

08:13.437 --> 08:15.762
The covenant is ratified in chapter 15.

08:16.034 --> 08:19.660
and it's signified in chapter 17 by circumcision.

08:19.760 --> 08:24.628
And it's an unconditional promise from God to Abram for three very specific things.

08:24.788 --> 08:27.572
Land, descendants, and a blessing.

08:27.633 --> 08:34.784
And in fact, tucked within that passage is a promise that from the descendants of Abram, all the nations of the earth will be blessed.

08:34.824 --> 08:43.538
It's very difficult to read the Abrahamic covenant without seeing the shadows of the birth of Jesus, who's the blessing from the line of Abraham for the entire earth.

08:43.682 --> 08:54.635
Now that's an interesting thing though for God to call Abram from Ur of the Chaldeans because according to Joshua 24 verse two, Abram's father and his family worshiped other gods.

08:55.216 --> 08:57.018
So they did not worship the one true God.

08:57.058 --> 08:58.800
They had no Bible at that time.

08:58.840 --> 09:00.862
They had no context for who God was.

09:01.403 --> 09:03.545
And yet God called Abram to come.

09:04.466 --> 09:05.087
And so he did.

09:05.107 --> 09:10.994
And in fact, if you look as the passage continues in verses five and following, Abram took Sarah, his wife,

09:11.362 --> 09:18.914
and Lotus nephew and all his possessions which he had accumulated and the persons which he had acquired in Huron and he set out for the land of Canaan.

09:19.395 --> 09:25.945
Thus they came to the land of Canaan and Abram passed through the land as far as the site of Shechem to the oak of Moray.

09:26.526 --> 09:28.610
And so he's going to begin to now settle in this land.

09:28.630 --> 09:34.639
But the question is how do you officially establish your sovereignty over land?

09:34.740 --> 09:38.706
How do you establish yourself as being the one who was in control

09:38.786 --> 09:39.847
of a specific region.

09:39.888 --> 09:44.113
While there were five critical steps that an ancient civilization took.

09:44.174 --> 09:46.617
They had no government to go to to get permission.

09:46.677 --> 09:52.585
They had no city council to go and request borders to be drawn.

09:52.665 --> 09:54.688
There was no city map that they could submit to.

09:54.708 --> 09:57.672
They literally did five very strategic things.

09:57.712 --> 10:00.556
The first thing they did is they built an altar.

10:00.937 --> 10:02.519
Look at verses seven and following.

10:03.440 --> 10:07.506
The Lord appeared to Abram and he said to your descendants, I will give this land.

10:07.874 --> 10:10.738
So he built an altar there to the Lord who had appeared to him.

10:10.758 --> 10:17.969
Then he proceeded from there to the mountains on the east of Bethel and he pitched his tent with Bethel on the west and AI on the east.

10:18.409 --> 10:23.497
And there he built an altar to the Lord and he called upon the name of the Lord.

10:23.937 --> 10:29.666
Now if you'll just glance down to chapter 13, he's gonna do it yet again in chapter 13 verse 18.

10:30.407 --> 10:35.474
It says that Abram moved his tent and came and dwelt by the oak of Mamre

10:35.938 --> 10:40.584
which was in Hebron, and there he built an altar to the Lord.

10:40.624 --> 10:49.114
So why is the first act when you enter the land in an ancient civilization in 2000 BC to establish your sovereignty over a region?

10:49.154 --> 10:51.938
Why is the first thing that you did to build an altar?

10:51.978 --> 10:53.320
Well, it showed a couple of things.

10:53.560 --> 10:58.546
One is it showed the priority of your life under the God that you served.

10:58.850 --> 11:03.835
So by building an altar, Abram was making himself distinct from the pagans nations around.

11:03.915 --> 11:07.639
He did not worship the God Kemash, or Molek, or the Asherah.

11:07.979 --> 11:09.641
No, he worshiped the one true God.

11:10.101 --> 11:18.270
And it also, in some ways, was a sign of worship and thanks to God who promised, I will give this land to you.

11:18.610 --> 11:21.253
And so he builds an altar in worship to God.

11:21.293 --> 11:24.436
The second thing you would do is you would walk the land.

11:24.636 --> 11:26.578
Look at chapter 13, verse 17.

11:27.330 --> 11:37.827
God says to Abram in Genesis 13, 17, to arise to walk about the land through its length and its breadth, for I will give it to you.

11:38.608 --> 11:40.271
Now, why would you walk the land?

11:40.932 --> 11:48.023
Well, if you're talking about modern community transformation, there's a phrase that's been used quite frequently.

11:48.043 --> 11:50.787
It's called asset-based community development.

11:50.807 --> 11:54.994
And it's basically a fancy way of saying, well, why don't you look around at what God has already provided?

11:55.106 --> 11:57.569
because God is doing an amazing thing all over.

11:57.629 --> 12:00.111
And so you look at what assets are already there.

12:00.132 --> 12:04.196
And so Abram did a little ABCDs of community transformation.

12:04.476 --> 12:09.722
He walked the land, the breadth of it, and the length of it, knowing God would give it to him.

12:10.102 --> 12:10.283
Why?

12:10.343 --> 12:13.006
Because the laws of real estate have not changed.

12:13.326 --> 12:15.649
There are three things about real estate that are important.

12:15.669 --> 12:18.412
Location, location, location.

12:18.432 --> 12:23.677
And so he walks the land, the breadth, and the length of it, and asks the question, can I grow anything here?

12:23.697 --> 12:24.338
Is it fertile?

12:24.898 --> 12:27.081
Is this a defensible space?

12:27.741 --> 12:32.787
Are there any high places that I could defend if one of these other city states came in and wanted to pick a fight?

12:32.827 --> 12:34.790
Do I have a place that I could defend?

12:35.350 --> 12:37.092
Is there trade around here?

12:37.613 --> 12:43.280
Are we close enough to the freeway that we can sell some things as people drive by or are we isolated?

12:43.800 --> 12:45.743
And then in that, is there a water source?

12:46.363 --> 12:48.185
Because without water, we're not going to survive.

12:48.246 --> 12:49.067
Is there a spring?

12:49.167 --> 12:50.268
Is there a well?

12:50.308 --> 12:50.929
Is there a river?

12:50.989 --> 12:52.050
Is there a something?

12:52.354 --> 12:54.256
It's asset-based community development.

12:54.276 --> 12:55.137
So he walks the land.

12:55.458 --> 13:02.246
Third thing he does, not just builds an altar, not just walks the land, but regarding water, he's going to dig a well.

13:02.326 --> 13:03.147
Turn to chapter 21.

13:04.669 --> 13:07.092
In chapter 21, Abram is going to dig a well.

13:07.853 --> 13:14.200
And he's going to have some conflict with Abimelech, which is the king of one of the other city states that are around.

13:14.801 --> 13:17.885
And his men come and seize the well from Abraham.

13:17.925 --> 13:22.290
So you've now got to fight over who really has ownership of the well.

13:22.562 --> 13:35.737
And in verse 25 of Genesis 21, Abraham now digs this well, it's seized by Abimelech's men and then in verse 27, he's gonna strike a deal with Abimelech and buy the well that he already dug himself.

13:35.837 --> 13:47.169
Now question, why if you were in ancient times, if you dug the well and there was a fight over the well, why on earth would you buy the well that you actually dug already?

13:47.870 --> 13:51.634
Well, you would do that most importantly so that you would have the receipt.

13:52.194 --> 13:53.897
We've now exchanged money.

13:54.558 --> 13:57.402
We're now in agreement this well, even though I dug it.

13:58.043 --> 13:58.503
Who cares?

13:58.844 --> 14:00.727
This well now that is for sale.

14:00.887 --> 14:01.528
I will buy it.

14:01.908 --> 14:02.850
And do we all agree?

14:02.870 --> 14:04.092
You get the money.

14:04.232 --> 14:04.973
I get the receipt.

14:05.093 --> 14:06.936
Abraham buys now the well.

14:07.877 --> 14:12.144
And so in verse 31, therefore he called the place Beersheba.

14:12.404 --> 14:15.809
You might know it as an ancient city mentioned in your Bible.

14:15.849 --> 14:16.370
In fact,

14:16.482 --> 14:25.655
It's mentioned over and over and over as the southernmost city, the boundaries of the people of the land that God would give Abram was from Dan in the north to Beersheba in the south.

14:25.675 --> 14:28.359
The word Beersheba really is a combination of two Hebrew words.

14:28.619 --> 14:30.221
It means the well of the oath.

14:30.802 --> 14:36.911
And in fact, it tells you there in verse 31, because these two, or rather these two, took an oath before the Lord.

14:36.951 --> 14:39.995
So he digs this well in Beersheba.

14:40.055 --> 14:42.098
Question, why would you dig a well?

14:42.882 --> 14:48.749
Well, one is it establishes a sense of ownership in that you're not going to dig a well and then tomorrow go down the road.

14:49.430 --> 14:53.876
So if you're taking all the time, energy and effort to dig a well, it expresses ownership.

14:54.396 --> 14:55.638
It expresses permanence.

14:56.739 --> 14:59.923
It's establishment of your presence there.

14:59.943 --> 15:04.148
But we have to remember what wells in this time were used for.

15:04.589 --> 15:06.771
A well was a place of commerce.

15:07.292 --> 15:10.676
So trade was taking place at the well because everybody needed water.

15:10.957 --> 15:12.178
So everybody came to the well.

15:12.770 --> 15:18.157
It was a place of social connection because people wanted to come and spend time together.

15:18.217 --> 15:19.478
Every family would need water.

15:19.498 --> 15:21.481
They'd all come to the well.

15:21.501 --> 15:29.971
Worth noting, by the way, in Genesis 24, Abraham is going to send to Elie Azar to find a wife for Isaac and he sends the servant to the well.

15:30.612 --> 15:35.317
And then in chapter 29, Jacob, when he's looking to find a wife, also goes to the well.

15:35.538 --> 15:38.922
All I'm saying is that good things can happen at the well.

15:39.102 --> 15:42.386
And so if you're looking for a spouse, you might be at the right place.

15:43.810 --> 15:45.773
And so he digs a well.

15:46.294 --> 15:50.801
The fourth thing that he did, he built an altar, walked the land, dug a well.

15:50.861 --> 15:53.866
The fourth thing that he did is he buried his dead.

15:54.347 --> 15:55.188
Look at chapter 27.

15:55.489 --> 16:01.518
In chapter 27, Abraham now is going to buy a cave in a field.

16:02.380 --> 16:06.386
And he's buying this cave so that he can bury Sarah, his wife, who has died.

16:06.850 --> 16:12.818
And the guy who owns the field in a similar way to the conflict over the well, this guy says, hey, don't worry about it.

16:12.878 --> 16:13.759
You can just have it.

16:14.080 --> 16:15.121
You don't need to buy it from me.

16:15.141 --> 16:15.882
You're a good neighbor.

16:16.343 --> 16:17.544
We've got a good relationship.

16:17.564 --> 16:18.346
Just bury your wife.

16:18.386 --> 16:18.886
No problem.

16:19.407 --> 16:23.412
And he says, no, tell me the price, not just of the cave, but of the field and all that's in it.

16:23.793 --> 16:24.454
I'm going to buy it.

16:24.494 --> 16:26.256
Now, why does Abraham buy it?

16:26.496 --> 16:31.403
Especially knowing that God said, arise, walk the land, the breadth of the length of it, for I will give it to you.

16:31.704 --> 16:33.366
God said, I'm going to give you this land.

16:33.726 --> 16:34.607
Why does he buy it?

16:34.748 --> 16:36.530
Again, he buys it so he can keep

16:36.706 --> 16:37.287
the receipt.

16:37.787 --> 16:52.606
And if you look at verse 17 now, he buys Ephron's field, which was in Makpela, which faced Mamre, the field in the cave, which was in it, all that the trees that were in the field, and there within all the confines of its border, they were deeded over to Abram.

16:53.768 --> 17:04.882
For a possession in front of the presence of all of the sons of Heth, before all that went at the gate of the city, after this Abram buried Sarah, his wife in the cave of the field, Makpela,

17:04.962 --> 17:07.925
facing Mamre that is Hebron in the land of Canaan.

17:08.326 --> 17:15.193
So the field in the cave and all that it's in it were deeded over to Abraham for a burial site by the sons of Heth.

17:15.213 --> 17:16.995
By the way, you can go to Israel today.

17:17.556 --> 17:19.638
You can go into the city of Hebron.

17:19.658 --> 17:30.329
There's a place called the tomb of the patriarchs where you can see the burial site of Abraham and his wife, Sarah, of Isaac and his wife, Rebecca and of Jacob and his wife, Leah.

17:30.770 --> 17:34.514
Question, why would you take all of the effort to bury

17:34.690 --> 17:35.211
You're dead.

17:35.871 --> 17:37.093
Well, a number of things.

17:37.393 --> 17:38.895
One is it honors your past.

17:39.676 --> 17:44.542
It's a recognition that we are where we are because of those who've gone before us.

17:45.243 --> 17:47.546
It's a sense of acknowledgement of history and heritage.

17:48.447 --> 17:55.115
It's a sense of celebrating the sacrifices of those who have gone before.

17:55.836 --> 18:02.024
And it's a way of looking back in the best of ways and realizing none of us got to where we are on our own.

18:02.665 --> 18:03.666
No one

18:03.746 --> 18:06.128
is a product of your own decisions.

18:06.188 --> 18:07.410
No person is an island.

18:07.430 --> 18:08.591
You've heard that expression before.

18:09.051 --> 18:16.659
And in a way, bearing your dead is an acknowledgement of we come from a long history and heritage of those who have gone before us.

18:17.339 --> 18:22.364
In the fifth and final thing, you would build an altar, walk the land, dig a well, bury your dead.

18:22.485 --> 18:25.528
Fifth and final, you would plant a tree.

18:25.548 --> 18:32.114
In verses 32 and following of Genesis 21, you're gonna see Abraham now,

18:32.706 --> 18:38.111
makes this covenant in Beersheba with Abimelech and Feikal, who's the commander of the army.

18:38.151 --> 18:41.775
He arises and he returns now to the land of the Philistines, they do at least.

18:42.275 --> 18:48.462
And then in verse 33, it says, Abraham planted a tamarisk tree in Beersheba.

18:48.862 --> 18:52.866
And there he called on the name of the Lord, the everlasting God.

18:53.687 --> 19:01.074
Now remember, Abraham was from ancient Sumer, which means he's an expert in all things concerning the desert.

19:01.538 --> 19:02.860
He knows what will grow.

19:02.900 --> 19:05.224
He knows horticulture.

19:05.304 --> 19:06.446
He knows agriculture.

19:06.466 --> 19:07.808
He knows irrigation.

19:08.429 --> 19:10.493
And he plants not just a tree.

19:11.114 --> 19:13.378
He plants what kind of tree?

19:13.398 --> 19:14.299
A tamarisk tree.

19:14.359 --> 19:15.601
That's very significant.

19:16.042 --> 19:17.905
What do we know about a tamarisk tree?

19:18.025 --> 19:19.508
Well, a few things.

19:19.648 --> 19:21.291
One, they're exceptionally hardy.

